            <div type="edition" subtype="section" n="i">
                <ab><lb n="1"/><persName><name key="Καλλίαρ">Καλλίαρ</name></persName>.
                   
            </ab></div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="section" n="ii">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name key="Ἡράκλης" type="divine">Ἡράκλεος</name></persName> ἱερά.
                </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation" subtype="section" n="i">
            <p>Kalliar.</p></div>
            <div type="translation" subtype="section" n="ii">
                <p>Sacred to Heracles.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The item is reported to be from Olympia, and it bears two separate inscriptions on
                    the mouth, written in two different hands and dialects (Elean and Ionic
                    respectively). The dedication to Heracles reveals that the contest ended in a
                    draw.  The hydria belongs to to the "ivy-leaf" group, which is dated to the
                    fifth century, but in this item the leafs are replaced with palamettes which
                    suggest that it dates to around the turn of the forth century BCE. </p></div>
            
